          "body": "Verses 7-21 are a case study in the simultaneity of faith and fear. Jacob prays one of the most theologically rich prayers in Genesis (32:9-12) — addressing God by covenant succession, quoting His specific command to return (cf. 31:3), confessing personal unworthiness, naming *chesed* and *emet*, and claiming the promise of innumerable seed (cf. 22:17; 28:14). Then, immediately after praying, he assembles 550 animals across multiple waves, deploys his servants with rehearsed scripts, and aims to 'cover/appease' (the verb is *kipher*, atonement vocabulary) Esau's face (32:20). The narrative does not condemn either action, but it does refuse to let them resolve the crisis. Neither prayer nor strategy crosses the Jabbok for him; the meeting at Peniel happens only when he has been emptied of both retinue and resources."
